   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_1812-08-14_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworths Town<lb/>
                  <date when="1812-07-22">August 14, 1812</date>
                  <lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute> Dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MileX1">Madam</persName>,<lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p> I felt <choice>
                  <orig>unwil-<lb/>
                    ling</orig>
                  <reg>unwilling</reg>
               </choice> to trouble you further<lb/>
                    about the little mistake in<lb/>
                    the quantity of the lace; but<lb/>
                    since you desire it I may<lb/>
                    venture. - Our Irish yards<lb/>
                    are not like our Irish miles<lb/>
                    longer than the English, but<lb/>
                    precisely the same &amp; lest you<lb/>
                    should have any doubts of<lb/>
                    the accuracy of measurement<lb/>
                    of our Irish fingers I enclose<lb/>
                    the whole of the lace is it came<lb/>
                    to us- It never was in any<lb/>
                    hands but those of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LongX1">Lord <choice>
                     <orig>Long<lb/>
                        ford</orig>
                     <reg>Longford</reg>
                  </choice>
               </persName>
               <lb/>
                    ford or his sister <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>rs. Hamilton</persName>
               <lb/>
                    who brought it over -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> We were obliged to get other<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_1812-08-14_page02.jpg"/>   
                    lace for our dresses, and as 3/4<lb/>
                    of a yard of the broad would<lb/>
                    be too little for the bosom of a gown<lb/>
                    &amp; a quarter pieced-on would<lb/>
                    look ugly &amp; <add>as</add> we don't want the<lb/>
                    narrow now, we should like<lb/>
                    to take any pretty <add>fine</add>white edging<lb/>
                    of any breadth, in exchange<lb/>
                    for <add>all</add>the lace, if the shopkeeper<lb/>
                    who sold it is willing to settle<lb/>
                    it in this manner - If not -<lb/>
                    we are quite <hi rend="underline">resigned</hi>, and<lb/>
                    beg that you will not be <choice>
                  <orig>con<lb/>
                        -cerned</orig>
                  <reg>concerned</reg>
               </choice>about it , for such things<lb/>
                    do not weigh heavily upon<lb/>
                    our spirits -<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> If you get the edging send it<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> wrapped in silver paper in<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_1812-08-14_page03.jpg"/>   
               the first frank Mr. Miles can<lb/>
               procure - not by Sir E B Little-<lb/>
               hales for I have promised<lb/>
               never to use his franking<lb/>
               privilege for any article of<lb/>
               dress --<lb/>
               Will you be so good my dear<lb/>
               Madame to write me a line<lb/>
               to say what the <hi rend="underline">gowns</hi> cost<lb/>
               exactly, as I am to divide the<lb/>
               piece with Mrs. E - and let<lb/>
               me know if I am any thing<lb/>
               in your debt.<lb/>
               <pb/>
               Though you say that we<lb/>
               must not hope to see you and<lb/>
               Mr. Miles this summer we<lb/>
               are persuaded that you will<lb/>
               take the first opportunity in<lb/>
               your power of coming to us<lb/>
            </p>
            <p> &amp; we thank you for saying that<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_1812-08-14_page04.jpg"/>   
               our little dirty channel shall<lb/>
               be no impediment<lb/>
               I am Dear Madame<lb/>
        
            </p>
            
            
            <closer> Yours sincerely<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName>
               <lb/>
               
               <lb/>
            </closer>
